			<div class="text" id="comment-73015666765">

				<strong class="title">Song Meaning</strong>Nwallace is one of the few here to mention segregation and civil rights.  Dylan sang Blowin' in 63, but wrote it a year earlier with folk singers Peter Paul and Mary having a top hit with it, Puff The Magic Dragon and Don't Think Twice before he did.    Blowin' does cover the universal wrongs, war and all that's been mentioned and to be sure the atomic bomb (but not yet Vietnam) was on our minds at the time, but I think the main "hit" of the song, at that time, was that of civil rights.   Like many of The Bard of that era's songs they lend themselves to a wide range of interpretations and that universality is surely why, as posters here mention, the songs remain fresh, can it be? 50 years later. <br />
<br />
A GREAT version of Blowin' in the Wind is that of Stevie Wonder singing the hell out of it on the Dylan's 30th Anniversary Tribute double CD. He has a couple minute spoken intro with a hint of the melody on piano and touches on the universal, but mentions apartheid in Africa etc.<br />
<br />
 The double DVD of the Tribute concert is surely a collector's item with John Cougar's killer rendition of Like a Rolling Stone all the other artist's versions of Dylan's songs......... it's worth it just for Stevie's Blowing in The Wind!     <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
				
